poem:
The Fogwhirl Flibberdance

Beware the dawn-breath, brumal-borne, the glimsy glister-gloom!  
The mizzle-murk creeps clobber-close, a shimmer-sham of shade;  
Its whiffle-whorls will waylay minds that wander through the gloam,  
For lurking leaps the Brimblenatch with snarly-sharp charade.  

He snicks his snicker-snackled claws, he rumbles rough and raw,  
He crackle-calls through crackling reeds with kerrang-knelling roar;  
He maw-gapes wide with wheezy-wheeze, a breath of bitter thaw,  
Then back he slinks through slithery sludge to skulk in fog once more.  

“Now hush, brave Hoddlehank!” I cried, “and heft the hurling-harp!  
We’ll hunt the hulking Brimblenatch before the sky grows gold;  
We’ll clink our clanker-cups of dusk, then twirl the twilight warp—  
Let shimmery shields and shimmer-spears in starlight stories told!”  

We whiffled forth through wobble-world where moonlight melts to mist,  
Past plip-plop puddles, purling pale, and whisper-willow trees;  
The fog-fangs hissed a hoary hymn, a hush-hush serpent-kissed,  
While drip-drum drizzles drubbed the dusk like distant drum-breeze seas.  

With flitter-flash of flamber-blade we found the foggy foe—  
Its glim-gleam eyes like glow-glass coals, its snarl a skirling storm;  
We clashed! Clang-clatter! Crack! It croaked, a keening overthrow;  
I thrust my thistle-thunder spear—shhhhhh—its misty heart grew warm.  

“Huzzah!” we hallooed, hooting high through honey-haloed haze;  
We hoisted high the fog-felled head, a trophy, pale and proud;  
We jigged a jubber-jinkled jig through dewdrop-dappled maze,  
Till sunrise rinsed the ragged realm in rose-gold ripple-cloud.  

Beware the dawn-breath, brumal-borne, the glimsy glister-gloom!

The Déjàjubjub’s Return

’Twas duskled in the mem’ry mists where zingzangs softly glide,  
A fizzled flicker fore-glow danced on paths we twice have trod;  
Beware the Déjàjubjub’s breath, beware its twin-eyed tide!  
It glurks in loops and lures the mind with dreams of dreams once flawed.  

He shivered in the zindle-shade, then slung the flashblade bright;  
He donned the helm of Hithertime and hummed the zither-song;  
The chimes of chrono-chains clanked close, a click-click-clack of right;  
With vorpal vim he vowed to cleave the coil where pasts belong.  

One whiffling step—then WHURR-WHURR-WHUMP!  The Déjàjubjub rose;  
Its eyes were spirals, spooling spools of seconds not yet spent;  
With snortled snarls and spiral-snaps it snapped at time-repose;  
Yet slash-blink-SNICK, the flashblade bit, loop-licking as it went!  

He hauled the head through hushlight halls where huzzahs hurled like rain;  
The timeturn tables twirled again, the clocks clanged claret-clear;  
They danced the dazzle-drummer dance, drank draughts of day-refrain;  
And every echo answered soft: “No twice is twice sincere.”  

’Twas duskled in the mem’ry mists where zingzangs softly glide,  
A fizzled flicker fore-glow danced on paths we twice have trod;  
We bear the Déjàjubjub’s crown—we carry time’s reprise inside;  
Yet every loop is lighter now where once the weight had clod.

The Whirlpoint of the Awlwhack   

Beware the blinkering braddlebeast, its glimgrin gonging wide,  
Through flinderfog it flarrows fast, a needlenight astride;  
The griptide grips with gnarling nails, the glishglade swallows sight—  
Heed hover-harps of heeding folk, whose murmurs croon of fright.  

Young Whimwatt whetted whistle-wood, his crindlecloak agleam;  
He honed the holspike halistone, the shard-edge of his dream;  
“O brindle-blade, be battle-bright, when braken shadows brawl—  
For I shall seek the sprocking Awl, that spins atop the thrall.”  

He tramppled through the twurling tuft, past crickle-creek and clam;  
With skrawk and skirl of scavenger fowl, the wumpfled forest sang.  
Snipwhirr! The windwind whirled its wings, the gritglass gorges clicked;  
Yet onward stomped the stalwart lad, where lesser hearts were licked.  

Lo! Glister-gashed in moonmire gleam, the Awlwhack rose—a tower!  
Its gimblegash of razored rings whirred snarl-snarra—Glower!  
Snick-snack! sang stonesteel in the night, and clatter-clang! the clash;  
Sparks spindled high like starry shrieks, a cracklefying flash.  

Then Whimwatt whirled his whistling wood, that thrumming thorn of war;  
He drove the drivning durdlespike clean through the shiver core.  
The Awlwhack yawed, a yawning hush; its whirliblades fell still—  
Sploorsh! the silence settled soft across the splantered hill.  

By crack of cloom he carried back the coolclasp clacking head;  
The villagers in vatfrock vests cavorted, quick to spread  
The table of triumphant tarts, tambourines, and teal—  
They clangored songs of clabbered hope beneath the candled wheel.  

Beware the blinkering braddlebeast—the glimgrin still is wide;  
Yet one bold boy with bark-bound nerve has bared the whirling tide.  
When flinderfog next flarrows near, remember Whimwatt’s call:  
He braved the black, he broke the spin—he bested the Awl!

**The Third Rail’s Jibber Jangle**

Beware the thrumming rail of gleam, that shivers night and day;  
Its zyntric buzz, a whisper‑wind, in tunnels deep it sways.  
A clangor’s call, a zrrzp! that cuts the silent sway, day;  
For lurking in the voltage veil, the Fraylix prowls, a spark‑born sway.  

I gird my glove with glintwust steel, the pulse I will outlast;  
A sheath of neon‑foam, my boots, to mute the rail’s fierce blast;  
With flicker‑fuse in pocket, I bind the surge, and hold my breath till silence lasts;  
The wind whirls whirring—hiss!—as I march, heart thudding fast, toward the humming blast.  

From shadows springs the Voxviper, its eyes of flicker‑flame;  
It snarls a zzz‑crack, a cracklethorn roar, to snarl the rail’s own name;  
I swing my glintwust blade, a glimmer‑gleam, and slay the fearsome flame;  
The rail goes quiet—whirr!—as the thrall is broke, the night now bears no name.  

Triumphant, I return with jubilees, the city lights aglow;  
The rail hum now a lullaby, a gentle roll of golden day;  
We dance on cobbles, clang‑clap—clack!—as dawn sings bright and low;  
Beware the thrumming rail of gleam, that shivers night and day.

The Shuttergleam

Hark, hobble-hush, ye nightward nomads: mind the shuttergleam that sighs;  
hush-snap!  
The silverfuzz will steal the spill, the filmfloss folds in tinny ties;  
clack-snap!  

Gather gossamer reels, grease the gears—wind spoolswirl till it rings;  
ring!  
Tether tape, braid the bulb, brace the back — braid brane for the bright-bell springs;  
ring.  

From the darkbox burst the Brimblejaw, brim-brum, blink-brella bold;  
whack!  
I raised a silver-saber, flashfork fang—snapcrunch!—took its teeth and told;  
smack!  

Home with humming harness, we carry darkmade dreams and reels of gold;  
beam!  
We hiss-hush, click-click, doff dust, dance the reelring—cheer the shutterbeam, bold.  
shutterbeam.

Beware the Agenda-Gnash

At noonish hush the glazegloom grew—tick-tock—a tempered doom,
Beware the Agenda-Gnash, my crew; its charts will chomp and chase;
Beware the splay of swivel-sway, the plug-vine tangle-bloom,
And shun the buzz-buzz bindersnap that snaps across your space.

He primed his pointer-saber—click!—for brisk agenda-solve;
Strapped on a notepad buckler bold, a lanyard-loop cuirass;
With coffee-crackle courage quick, his focus firmed resolve;
He paced the projector-prairie pale, past panes of panel-glass.

Out from the quartzwhite screen it slid—whirr, clack—an office drawl;
The Agenda-Gnash with piechart jaws and spreadsheet-scything stare;
Its laser-lash and pointer-poke went ping-pang, primed to maul;
While memodust and marker-mist made migraine-colored glare.

I raised the clicker-scythe and leapt—ka-CHAK!—through swivel-thud;
We grappled in clatter-cascade storm, in knotted cable-snare;
I cleft its gantt-gullet clean in twain; out poured a graphy flood;
Then stillness settled, soft as slides, unspooling from the snare.

Now noonish hush in glazeglow gleams; tick-tock turns tame the room;
We jingled cupclink-chorus bright and stapled smiles in place;
No swivel-sway nor plug-vine snarl; fresh flipcharts fizz and bloom;
All hail the minutes, mended neat; hooray for homely grace.

Where once the glazegloom grew and tick-tock tolled of doom,
No more the Agenda-Gnash shall gnaw nor shadow meeting space;
Now giggle-light and stapler-sunbeam brim the braveboard room;
So share the snap of snacktime cheer and set a kinder pace.
